IP addressing 

IP = Internet Protocol Address

Definition:
An IP address is a unique numerical identifier assigned to every device 
(computer, smartphone, server, printer, etc.) connected to a network that 
uses the Internet Protocol for communication.

Think of it like:
├─ Physical address (street address) for physical mail
├─ Phone number for phone calls
├─ Email address for emails
└─ IP address for data packets on networks

Real-World Analogy:
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Sending Physical Mail                       │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Sender's Address: 123 Main St               │
│ Receiver's Address: 456 Oak Ave             │
│ Postal Service Routes Mail                  │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Sending Data Packets (IP)                   │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Sender's IP: 192.168.1.5                    │
│ Receiver's IP: 8.8.8.8                      │
│ Internet Routes Data                        │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘

Why IP Addresses Matter:
✓ Unique identification of devices
✓ Routing packets across networks
✓ Enabling communication between devices
✓ Network management and security
✓ Load balancing and traffic routing


IPv4 Address Format:

192.168.1.5
│   │    │  │
│   │    │  └─ Octet 4 (Host)
│   │    └───── Octet 3 (Host/Subnet)
│   └────────── Octet 2 (Subnet)
└────────────── Octet 1 (Network)

Each Octet:
├─ Range: 0-255 (8 bits = 256 possible values)
├─ Separated by dots (.)
├─ Written in decimal (not binary)
└─ Example: 192.168.001.005 (leading zeros optional)

Total IPv4 Addresses:
4 octets × 8 bits each = 32 bits total
2^32 = 4,294,967,296 total possible addresses

IPv4 Classes (Older Classification - Still Important):

┌─────────┬──────────────────┬──────────┬──────────────────┐
│ Class   │ First Octet Range│ Example  │ Total Hosts      │
├─────────┼──────────────────┼──────────┼──────────────────┤
│ Class A │ 1-126            │ 10.0.0.0 │ 16 Million       │
│         │ (0 reserved,     │ /8       │ per network      │
│         │  127 loopback)   │          │                  │
├─────────┼──────────────────┼──────────┼──────────────────┤
│ Class B │ 128-191          │172.16.0.0│ 65,536 hosts     │
│         │                  │ /16      │ per network      │
├─────────┼──────────────────┼──────────┼──────────────────┤
│ Class C │ 192-223          │192.168.. │ 254 hosts        │
│         │                  │.0 /24    │ per network      │
├─────────┼──────────────────┼──────────┼──────────────────┤
│ Class D │ 224-239          │224.0.0.0 │ Multicast        │
│         │                  │          │ (special use)    │
├─────────┼──────────────────┼──────────┼──────────────────┤
│ Class E │ 240-255          │240.0.0.0 │ Reserved         │
│         │                  │          │ (experimental)   │
└─────────┴──────────────────┴──────────┴──────────────────┘

Note: CIDR notation (/8, /16, /24) is now preferred over class-based

IPv4 Address Ranges:

Public IP Ranges (Routable on Internet):
├─ 1.0.0.0 to 9.255.255.255
├─ 11.0.0.0 to 172.15.255.255
├─ 172.32.0.0 to 192.167.255.255
├─ 192.169.0.0 to 198.18.255.255
├─ 198.20.0.0 to 223.255.255.255
└─ Can be accessed from internet

Private IP Ranges (RFC 1918 - NOT Routable):
├─ 10.0.0.0 to 10.255.255.255 (10/8)
│  └─ 16,777,216 addresses - Used in organizations
├─ 172.16.0.0 to 172.31.255.255 (172.16/12)
│  └─ 1,048,576 addresses - Used in organizations
├─ 192.168.0.0 to 192.168.255.255 (192.168/16)
│  └─ 65,536 addresses - Most common (home routers)
└─ Cannot be accessed directly from internet

Special Addresses:

127.0.0.1 - Localhost (Your Own Machine)
├─ Also called "loopback"
├─ Points to your own computer
├─ Entire 127.0.0.0/8 range is reserved
└─ 127.0.0.1 most common

0.0.0.0 - All Addresses
├─ Represents "any" or "all"
├─ Used in routing: "default route"
├─ Used in listening: "listen on all interfaces"
└─ Never sent on network

255.255.255.255 - Broadcast
├─ Special broadcast address
├─ Sends to all devices on network
├─ Example: 192.168.1.255 broadcasts to all on 192.168.1.0/24
└─ Not routable beyond local network

169.254.0.0/16 - Link-Local
├─ Self-assigned when DHCP fails
├─ Device assigns itself IP from this range
├─ Indicates configuration problem
└─ Example: 169.254.42.1
